context: In <a0_0><b4_0><b5_0>Europe<b5_0/><b4_0/><a0_0/>, the copyright infringement case Public Relations Consultants Association Ltd v Newspaper Licensing Agency Ltd had two prongs; one concerned whether a news aggregator service infringed the copyright of the <a1_0><b6_0>news generators<b6_0/><a1_0/>; the other concerned whether the temporary web cache created by the web browser of a consumer of the aggregator's service, also infringed the copyright of the news generators. The first prong was decided in favor of the news generators; in <a2_0><b7_0>June 2014<b7_0/><a2_0/> the second prong was decided by the Court of Justice of the European Union (CJEU), which ruled that the <a3_0><b8_0>temporary web cache of consumers<b8_0/><a3_0/> of the aggregator did not infringe the copyright of the news generators.
